              <div class="text-content Normal_External_642_66" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; " class="Title">Here we shall learn how to build a SIESTA input file for the graphene nanoribbon N-AGNR depicted below (for N=11):</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 226px; width: 413px;  height: 226px; left: 143px; position: absolute; top: 68px; width: 413px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_3 stroke_0">
              <img src="1_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2019.41.39.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 226px; width: 414px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id3" style="height: 145px; left: 39px; position: absolute; top: 297px; width: 637px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_637_145" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style"><span class="style_1">1.</span> Input <span class="style_2">graphene.fdf</span> file with the graphene sheet primitive cell (2 atoms): type <span class="style_3">4 </span>and then give the name of the input file<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><span class="style_1">2.</span> Go to the <span class="style_4">M</span> menu by typing <span class="style_3">M</span>. The lattice vectors are shown at the top of the menu (below). They are depicted on the picture above in blue as well.<br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 131px; width: 639px;  height: 131px; left: 38px; position: absolute; top: 435px; width: 639px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke">
              <img src="1_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2016.57.19.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 132px; width: 639px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 122px; left: 36px; position: absolute; top: 569px; width: 641px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_641_122" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1">Notice the REFERENCE system in which lattice vectors at the moment are the same. The lattice vector we have are not particularly appropriate for the nanoribbon we want to build. We need something like the vectors shown in red on the same picture above.<br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id5" style="height: 214px; left: 33px; position: absolute; top: 699px; width: 324px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_324_214" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_1">3.</span> Make an extension of the lattice using the option <span class="style_3">Su</span> with the 3x3 matrix:<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2">        <span class="style_3"> -1   2   0<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_3">          1   0   0<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_2"><span class="style_3">          0   0   1<br /></span></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3">   <br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 162px; width: 241px;  height: 162px; left: 382px; position: absolute; top: 731px; width: 241px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_3 stroke_1">
              <img src="1_files/Screen%20shot%202011-04-17%20at%2019.50.46.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 163px; width: 241px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id6" style="height: 283px; left: 332px; position: absolute; top: 1228px; width: 300px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content Normal_External_300_283" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="Normal">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_1"><span class="style_1">4.</span> Make another, this time diagonal,  extension along the 2nd lattice vector: use <span class="style_3">Ex</span> with<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_1">            0 0 and  0 5 and  0 0<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_3"> <br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_3">This will produce a supercell with 24 atoms (left). The lattice vectors are shown below.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


